Bellabeat Case Study

by Sanjay Paul on March 14, 2022

Case Study: How Can a Wellness Technology Company Play It Smart?

Introduction

Bellabeat is a small but successful high-tech company & manufacturer of health-focused smart products for women that are designed to analyze fitness data. They have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. Companys products include a health tracking app, wellness tracking bracelets, watches, and a water bottle that tracks daily water intake.

Urka Sren and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women. By 2016, Bellabeat had opened offices around the world and launched multiple products. Bellabeat has become a widely successful company, and they are looking to grow the company. Sren knows that an analysis of Bellabeats available consumer data would reveal more opportunities for growth.

Some of companys products are:

  • Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. This data can help users better understand their current habits and make healthy decisions. The Bellabeat app connects to their line of smart wellness products.

  • Leaf: Bellabeats classic wellness tracker can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat app to track activity, sleep, and stress.

  • Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide you with insights into your daily wellness.

  • Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake using smart technology to ensure that you are appropriately hydrated throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to track your hydration levels.

  • Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also offers a subscription-based membership program for users. Membership gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

Ask / Task

Stakeholders:

  • Urka Sren: Bellabeats cofounder and Chief Creative Officer

  • Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeats cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team

  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team

Goal of Analysis:

Analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into existing competitor or how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices. and apply these insights to in your presentation for answers to below questions.

Key Questions:

1. Explore data to find out what are some trends in smart device usage?

2. Out line the trend & How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy & share analysis and recommendations?

Prepare

We will use the public dataset FitBit Fitness Tracker Data from Kaggle, a Public Domain, dataset made available through Mobius. This dataset was generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016.

Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Individual reports can be parsed by export session ID (column A) or timestamp (column B). Variation between output represents use of different types of Fitbit trackers and individual tracking behaviors / preferences.

Download and unzip the 18 CSV documents and began exploration

This data has limited insight due to only being thirty people used for the survey. Also the demographics of this group is anonymous. and participants age, gender, and lifestyle are unknown. Bellabeats is a health tracking company targeted for women so data given specifically by women with more sample size would have been ideal for this analysis. Initially we can check the data in spreadsheets and then upload them to suitable program. Here R Studio will be used to complete this analysis.

Dataset contains categories of data tables such as :

  • Daily records(Activity, calories, Intensities, steps)

  • Hourly Records ( Calories, Intensities, steps)

  • By minutes records( Calories, Intensities, METs, steps and sleep)

  • Sleep record

  • Heart rate record

  • Weight log

Some of the data in tables isnt in consistent or correct format, so process the data & checking for errors, cleaning, merging and formatting data before start analysis. also need to convert Date in the format which shows Day of the week. As well as the ActivityHour had date comined. Formatting this data to separate Date and time. This allowed me to get Day of the week as well as time.

Some of the atrributes are redudant in datasets so we are going to take few datasets and merging few datasets to reduce the redundancy attributes.

Merging datasets

  • hourly_calories

  • hourly_intensities

  • hourly_steps

  • minute_calories

  • minute_intensities

  • minute_steps

hourly_activity0 <-merge(x = hourly_calories, y = hourly_intensities , by = c("Id", "ActivityHour"), all = TRUE)
hourly_activity <-merge(x = hourly_activity0, y = hourly_steps, by = c("Id", "ActivityHour"), all = TRUE)
minute_activity0 <-merge(x = minute_calories, y = minute_intensities, by =c("Id", "ActivityMinute"), All = TRUE)
minute_activity <- merge(x = minute_activity0, y = minute_steps, by = c("Id", "ActivityMinute"), All = TRUE)

Now we have following datasets : daily_activity, hourly_activity, minute_activity, sleep_day, weight_log

Lets check the data integrity Since 30 fitbit users provided their data there should be 30 unique Ids.Checking the datasets using n_distinct function which count the number of unique values.

n_distinct(daily_activity$Id)
## [1] 33
n_distinct(hourly_activity$Id)
## [1] 33
n_distinct(minute_activity$Id)
## [1] 33
n_distinct(sleep_day$Id)
## [1] 24
n_distinct(weight_log$Id)
## [1] 8

After checking above values, its clear that:

  • (daily_activity,hourly_activity and minute_activity) has 33 unique Ids which is more 30 users.

  • sleep_day dataset has 24 unique Ids which is less than 30 users.

  • weight_log has only 8 unique Ids which is way less than 30 users, so if we use this dataset it will be difficult to make conclusions. but we will try to look into the BMI with data.

Checking duplicates and NA values

Duplicated function returns the duplicated values and is.na function returns the NA values. Here we are using sum function to count the duplicated and NA values in the datasets.

Renaming column names

All the datasets daily_activity, hourly_activity, minute_activity and sleep_day has date and are in different column names and in character datatype. So we are going to format the column names.

daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% rename(Date = ActivityDate)
hourly_activity <- hourly_activity %>% rename(Date = ActivityHour)
minute_activity <- minute_activity %>% rename(Date = ActivityMinute)
sleep_day <- sleep_day %>% rename(Date = SleepDay)

Formatting datatype

All the datasets has date column and it is a charater datatype. Changing them to date and time format.

daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% mutate(Date = as.POSIXct(Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y"))
hourly_activity <- hourly_activity %>% mutate(Date = as.POSIXct(Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone()))
minute_activity <- minute_activity %>% mutate(Date = as.POSIXct(Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone()))
sleep_day <- sleep_day %>% mutate(Date = as.POSIXct(Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone()))

Seperating column

Seperating the date column in hourly_activity & minute_activity dataset as date and time column for further analysis. Analysing activity and changes in them on hourly basis might be very useful insights.

hourly_activity <- hourly_activity %>% separate(Date, c("Date", "Time"), sep = " ")
minute_activity <- minute_activity %>% separate(Date, c("Date", "Time"), sep = " ")

For general fitness, most adults should aim for 10,000 steps per day. This figure may rise or fall depending on a persons age, current fitness level, and health goals. This recommendation comes from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). Here we can analyse that average step count it is low. same for other observations too. recommended average distance 8 kilometers or 5 miles. as per google data,By age 75+, people are sedentary for 11 hours per day i.e 660 minutes and here the average counts to even more than this figure.

The CDC also recommends adults getting 150 minutes of physical activity each week, including aerobic activity and muscle-strengthening activity. This can be 30 minutes a day, five days a week. Of the 150 minutes of exercise, 75 minutes needs to be vigorous exercise. In this group, users are getting about 21 minutes of vigorous exercise a day, which equals about 147 minutes of vigorous exercise. Here users are exceeding the recommended amount of vigorous exercise.

Now lets also do small BMI analysis then we will proceed to share and visualize our analysis.

stakeholders Want an analysis of consumers use of an existing competitor/product to identify trends that may lead to potential opportunities for growth. The following charts show the correlation between activity and reaching recommendations.

First we are check the usage of device while in sleep and while being active. for this we will calculate the usage percentage in both the stage.

active_time <- daily_activity %>% select(LightlyActiveMinutes, FairlyActiveMinutes, VeryActiveMinutes, SedentaryMinutes)

Avg_Active_time =  (mean(active_time$VeryActiveMinutes) + mean(active_time$FairlyActiveMinutes) + mean(active_time$LightlyActiveMinutes)) 

Total_Active_time = sum(mean(active_time$LightlyActiveMinutes), mean(active_time$FairlyActiveMinutes), mean(active_time$VeryActiveMinutes), mean(active_time$SedentaryMinute))

Active_percentile <- (Avg_Active_time / Total_Active_time ) * 100

sleep_Percentile <- (mean(sleep_day$TotalMinutesAsleep) / max(sleep_day$TotalMinutesAsleep) * 100)
Usage <- c('Active_Usage', 'Sleep_Usage')
Percentile <- c(Active_percentile, sleep_Percentile)
Device_Usage <- data.frame(Usage, Percentile)
Device_Usage
##          Usage Percentile
## 1 Active_Usage   18.67011
## 2  Sleep_Usage   52.65995
ggplot(Device_Usage, aes(x="", y=Percentile, fill=Usage)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1, color='black')+
  coord_polar("y", start=0)+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(axis.title.x= element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(), 
        panel.grid = element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=16, face = "bold")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("green","blue")) +
  geom_text(aes(label = Percentile),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+
  labs(title="Device Usage")

The pie chart shows that users are using their device more while sleep then while being active.

Adressing Data limitations

As we know when it comes to maintaining health, there are lot of factors that needs to be considered, such as Age,diet, users personal goals and their lifestyles. Also it is good to consider all medical conditions, as the bodys requirements changes based on it. All this information is lacking in the given Dataset and can be encouraged to gather more of above information, to know more about users and help them based on their personal needs and requirements.

Lets proceeds to the final phase of this analysis.

Act / Recommendation

Bellabeats product can give a holistic approach to health for woman. with its product, users can gain such valuable insight into various areas of wellness and stress sensitivity.

Below recommendation are for stakeholders which can be considered for marketing strategy and actions.

Recommendations for the Future data collection & analysis:

  • Since the sample size is very low and only one smart device (Fitbit) is considered for the analysis. So another survey needs to be conducted and that should include at least 5 other top smart device users.
  • Ensure to reach the survey to more women and include locations as well.
  • Make sure to enhance the sample as much as possible.
  • More qualitative data needs to be included to understand the users on an emotional level, demographic level & gender level.
  • Should be Longer data collection period.

Recommendations for marketing the bellabeats product base on leaf & time but both connected to the app:

  • The users must be educated more regarding the importance of physical activity and tracking them in their daily life so they can improve or maintain them.They need to be aware about the benefit of tracking their physical activity so that they use the device or product more.
  • Bellabeat product or services must send alert to the users Whenever the user is found to be sitting idle or inactive for a longer period of time, the app must alert the user to take a walk or do some sort of a physical activity. update or notify user frequently for the activities which is being tracked and also if there is any goal achieved or missed.
  • Notify the users with Alarm feature for water intakes and hydration level, Steps to complete and also notify if user is in bed but not asleep for long time.
  • Bellabeat must include features like BMI notification, also allow users to track their Menstrual cycles.
  • Allow users to add goals to their apps and devices or product can suggest goals too. and if they are achieved, some kind of rewards can be given to users.
  • Bellabeat also can start a counseling service for the users to guide them to achieve their goal.
